Part I - Project: Investigate Ford GoBike System Dataset¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 65,819 individual rides in the dataset with 16 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip)Your answer here!

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the duration of bike rides in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that riders' age will have a great effect on the riders' durations. I also think that members' gender and user type will play a big part in the length of their bike rides.

def count_plot(x_var):
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    sns.countplot(data = df, x = x_var, color = base_color)
    plt.yticks([0, 10000, 20000, 30000, 40000, 50000],[0, '10k', '20k', '30k', '40k','50k'])

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration_min data was skewed to the right hence I transformed the X axis using logarithimic function. After the transformation, it showed the data had a normal distribution with the peak at 8-10 minutes. I also perfromed a log transformation on the age distribution histogram.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • First, I changed the duration from seconds to minutes by dividing it by 60 for easier interpretation because we are used to working with minutes. The outliers detected on the histogram were removed.
  • Second, I calculated the age of members using the member_birth_year data because I wanted to use age in my analysis. The data was obtained in 2019 hence this was the Year used in the calculation.
  • Third, after obtaining the age I noticed there were some outliers on the data, ie several people above 100 year old, and since this data is about bike riding, this doesn't seem practical and hence the outliers were removed.

By looking at the heatmap, it can be noted that most frequent riders are aged between 25 and 40. There is also an inverse relationship between duration of a ride and age of a rider, ie the younger a rider is the longer the trip. Older riders tend to have shorter trips.

Bivariate Exploration of categorical variables¶

In [21]:
#create a function for ploting a violinplot and a box plot to visualize one quantitative and one qualitative variable
def sub_plot (x_axis, y_axis):
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.violinplot(x_axis, y_axis, data=df, color=base_color, inner=None)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.boxplot(x_axis, y_axis, data=df, color=base_color)

#create a function for count plots
def count_plot(x_axis, hue):
    sns.countplot( x=x_axis, hue=hue, data = df,)
    ticks=[0, 5000, 10000, 15000, 20000, 25000, 30000, 35000, 40000]
    plt.yticks(ticks,[0, '5k', '10k', '15k', '20k', '25k', '30k', '35k', '40k'])

Males make up for most rides recorded. Also all genders prefer having a subscription.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Riders of different ages and genders take different lengths of trips. The shorter trips are made by younger riders, while older riders tend to take longer durations. It is also interesting to see that females took longer trips as compared to the other genders.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I expected the subsribers to have longer trips but customers were the ones with longer durations. Also, I expected the frequency of rides to be almost evenly distributed among the genders but the males' counts was much highers compared to the rest.

In [29]:
def fg(x):
    g = sns.FacetGrid(data = df, col = x, size = 5, margin_titles = True)
    g.map(plt.scatter, 'member_age', 'duration_min', alpha=0.25)
